        "text": "<@U07H6E54FEH> and <@U027JEHGZRA> just catching up with things here after a busy period and some leave.\n\n• I have approved the GitHub app, although the messages above suggest it was here already? Maybe some additional permission were needed, but it should be fully functional now. (We require approval on apps as the free Slack has a cap on the number of apps we can install).\n• This channel is primarily for discussion of translations of material in the core code base (hence \"core-translation\"). Currently this is errors, warnings and messages in base R and messages in the Windows GUI; we also cover the recommended packages and macOS GUI. I will update the description to clarify (subject to word limit!). So:\n    ◦ Advertising and briefly discussing other translation projects is okay, but I wouldn't subscribe to related repos here. Instead start a new channel and advertise it here. Maybe #datatable-translation and #cheatsheet-translation?\n    ◦ Subscribing to PRs on r-devel\/translations on this channel makes sense. I see Christian tried to do that, but I'm not sure it worked, so I'll try again.\n• Adding CODEOWNERS to r-devel repos was identified as a best practice in the guide created at R Dev Day @ RSECon25: <https:\/\/github.com\/r-devel\/repo-best-practices>. Implementing these best practices is something we can work on in the upcoming R Dev Days (Oct 7-8, UK; <https:\/\/pretix.eu\/r-contributors\/r-dev-day-oz-25\/|Nov 21, Australia>, Dec 16-17, Auckland \/ Virtual) and something that others could contribute to once we can get issues set up (or even before!). We do have a <https:\/\/github.com\/orgs\/r-devel\/teams\/translations|GitHub translations team> who should probably be CODEOWNERS for the translations repo.\n• The french translation has historically been led by Philippe Grosjean via <https:\/\/github.com\/phgrosjean\/rfrench>, which I see Christian has contributed to. Philippe is not on this Slack, but he is on our GitHub translations team and also on Weblate, so I would definitely recommend Christian to liaise with Philippe to ensure Weblate translations are kept in sync with GitHub contributions (going forward we would recommend to use Weblate, but external translations can be uploaded to Weblate with control over how to handle conflicts).\n• We continue to work on maintaining a common glossary across languages and across translation projects. A little more work was done on a related package at R Dev Day @ RSECon25: <https:\/\/github.com\/r-devel\/glossary>.",
